<h3 id="sfx" class="mt-2 underline">SFX</h3>
<p> We were inspired by Lil Gator Game and Stardew Valley. 
    For general purpose sound effects and beep speech, we used Lil Gator Game. 
    For ambience and footsteps, we looked at Stardew Valley.
</p>

<h2 id="process" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">General Process</h2>
<p class="mb-2"> For all audio, we found free sound effects which we could use as placeholders, so we could implement them into the game engine.</p>
<p class="mb-2"> Then, once we found final assets, we could drag them into the engine (since implementation would already be taken care of).</p>
<p> We followed a strict pipeline of getting assets into the engine, which included editing the sounds and using proper naming conventions (see the Audio Bible for more).</p>

<h2 id="sfxp" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">SFX Process</h2>
<p class="mb-2">We divided SFX into several categories: General SFX, Ambience, Footsteps, and Beep Speech.</p>
<p> For these sounds, we sourced free assets (CC0) from
    <a class="text-green-600 dark:text-green-300" href="http://freesound.org" target="_blank">freesound.org</a>, 
    then processed the sounds in Audacity or Reaper, before importing them into Reaper.
</p>

<h2 id="musicp" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Music Process</h2>
<p class="mb-2"> For writing music, generally, we would start by creating a melody and bassline, followed by creating a matching chord progression and percussion line. Then, we’d repeat the process for a B section.</p>
<p class="mb-2"> For each track, we would use basic instruments that roughly estimated the sound we were aiming for using the free Spitfire LABS plugin. Then, once the song was finished, we would pick final instruments using the Kontakt 8 plugin.</p>

